John Edward: Language skills are a must for global citizens
The Scottish Independent Schools have a track record of academic achievement, which continues in 2018 with further excellent test results, individual and group successes in sport, the arts, music and other community activities.
These schools have over 30 000 pupils across Scotland, are represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools ( SCIS) and strive to provide the best possible level of service to their pupils and parents.
Independent schools prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen careers and their place as global citizens.
As the education sector can design and implement tailored school curricula, we see that modern languages are increasingly popular and in demand in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to a person in a language they understand, it goes right to their head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes straight to his heart.
It's a significant observation that if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries, we can't rely on English alone.
The latest results of this year's tests show that languages are at the top of the charts, with independent schools having the lowest achievement rates.
A total of 68 percent of students who learned a foreign language scored the highest A's.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools show that the highest A scores were achieved by 72 percent of Mandarin students, 72 percent of German students, 69 percent of French students, and 63 percent of Spanish students.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are promoting foreign languages as important skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages as subjects of choice are given equal weight in the curricula of independent and other schools as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics).
A survey carried out by the UK's Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 showed that the reasons employers cite as problems in filling vacancies are 17 per cent lack of language skills.
Language skills are therefore increasingly becoming essential in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more job opportunities require languages, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Whatever career a person chooses, learning a second language will have the real advantage of being a lifelong skill in the future.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries automatically gives a person who speaks more than one language an advantage over the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, with the only language spoken by the double-digit percentage of people, 15 percent, being French.
That's why it's important for children today to invest in language learning.
If children know more languages, especially those of emerging economies, they will have a better chance of finding meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, each school differs in the languages it teaches.
Many schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages considered to be the most important for the UK in the 2020 outlook, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the child's interest, independent schools will always have a choice of languages with teachers who are experts in the field.
Independent schools in Scotland are dedicated to providing an educational environment that prepares and equips children with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future may hold.
At this point, there is no denying that languages are essential to the future of a country in a global business environment, and that this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be considered as international communication skills
Independent schools will continue to offer young people in Scotland this choice, diversity and excellence.
It must be done.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
