The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end, a girl came to me and said, "Why are you telling me this now, in my senior year?"
She said that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me, he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was first introduced this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance and improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students had been seriously sleep-deprived for a week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
One part is a picture of college campuses where students click on coffee mugs, curtains, sneakers, and books about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep and the importance of proper sleep habits.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation may increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The campus map with interactive icons then encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
We know that student behavior won't change overnight.
But we think they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes", Professor Czeisler added.
The culture of "all-night study" still exists, he added, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean that the problem of sleep deprivation is also growing.
Getting enough quality sleep should be the student's secret weapon to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said -- even to prevent weight gain, because sleep deprivation puts the brain into a hunger mode, so you're always hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design a course that one of his classes took last year during his freshman year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push for the whole course.
He hopes to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar programme of study before entering a competitive institution.
