Mickelson, who was out of shape, came off the bench at the Ryder Cup on Saturday.
American Phil Mickelson would have set the record on Sunday with 47 Ryder Cup games, but he'd have to tune in to prevent it from being an unfortunate milestone.
Mickelson, who played in the biennial event for a record 12th time, was sent to the bench by Captain Jim Furyk for the Saturday Fourball and Foursome.
Instead of being the center of the action, as was often the case in the U.S., the five-time major winner spent his day alternating between cheerleading and working on a play in a sequence that he hoped would fix what was bothering him.
The 48-year-old has never been the most direct of drivers, even at the peak of his career, so he's not an ideal choice for the narrow Le Golf National course, where the long, jagged terrain routinely punishes stray shots.
And if the golf course itself isn't alarming enough, Mickelson faces the ninth Sunday match against the defending British Open champion Francesco Molinari, who, in a team with rookie Tommy Fleetwood, has won all four of his matches this week.
If the Americans, who were four points behind, had started 12 separate swords, avoided a quick start, Mickelson's bat could have proved absolutely crucial.
Furyk expressed confidence in his husband and added nothing else.
"He completely understood the role he had today, he slapped me on the back, put his hand around my shoulder and said he would be ready tomorrow", Furyk said.
He's so confident in himself.
He's a member of the Straw Syndicate, and he's been so helpful to these teams in the past and this week.
I guess I just couldn't imagine him playing two swords.
I imagined more, but that's how it turned out, and we thought we had to go this way.
He wants to participate, like everyone else.
Mickelson will surpass Nick Faldo's record for most Ryder Cup Wests played on Sunday.
It could mean the end of a Ryder Cup career that never reached the heights of his individual record.
Mickelson has 18 wins, 20 losses and seven draws, although Furyk says his presence has brought certain intangible results to the team.
"He's funny, sarcastic, funny, likes to make fun of people, and he's a great team room companion", he explained.
I think the younger players had fun coming to him this week, which was fun to watch.
It's giving a lot more than just a game.
European Captain Thomas Bjorn knows that the great leadership may soon disappear
Thomas Bjorn, the European captain, knows from experience that the big lead in singles from the last few days in the Ryder Cup can easily turn into an uncomfortable ride.
Dane made his debut in 1997 at Valderrama, where the team led by captain Seve Ballesteros had a five-point lead over the Americans, but they came into the final with a very close 141⁄2-131⁄2.
"You have to remember that we had a big lead at Valderrama, as well as in Brooklyn where we lost, and at Valderrama where we won, but only narrowly", said Bjorn, pictured, after watching the 2018 season win 5-3 on Friday and yesterday to lead Le Golf National 10-6.
So history and every member of that team showed me that we're not over.
You'll be bored tomorrow.
Go out there and do all the right things.
It's not over until all those points are on the board.
We have a goal, and that's to try and win the trophy, and that's what we're focused on.
I said I'll focus on the 12 players on our side, but we also know what to stand for on the other side.
Bjorn, pleased with the way his players were doing on the complex golf course, added: "I could never have done it alone.
We're gonna have another animal tomorrow.
Tomorrow is the preparation of individual performances, and it's very difficult.
It's great to be out with a partner when it's going well, but when you're out there on your own, your golfing ability is fully tested.
That's the message you have to give to the players, to get the best out of yourself tomorrow.
Now you're leaving your partner behind, and he has to go and get the best out of himself, too.
Unlike Bjorn, opponent Jim Furyk will make sure his players play better as individuals than as partners, with the exceptions of Jordan Spieth and Justin Thomas, who scored three points out of four.
Furyk was personally on both sides of these great turning points, when he was part of the winning team in Brooklyn, only to end up as the loser when Europe achieved the "Miracle in Medina".
"I remember every damn word", he said when asked how Ben Crenshaw, the 1999 captain, encouraged his players to focus on the final day.
Tomorrow we have 12 big games, but you'd like to start fast like in Brooklyn, like in Medina.
When this pace goes one way, it puts a lot of pressure on the midfield.
So we set up the lineup and made sure the boys felt like, you know, like we were gonna do magic tomorrow.
Thomas was tasked with trying to lead the counterattack and face Rory McIlroy in a top-flight match with Paul Casey, Justin Rose, Jon Rahm, Tommy Fleetwood and Ian Poulter, who are the other Europeans in the top half of the standings.
"I went with this group of boys in this order, because I think it covers the whole way", Bjorn said of his singles selection.
German new warship still re-delayed
The newest German naval frigate was approved in 2014 to replace aging Cold War-era warships, but will not be available for at least another year due to faulty systems and a snow-covered coastline, local media report.
The launch of the lead ship, the Rheinland-Pfalz, a brand new Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigate, has now been postponed to the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, citing an army spokesman.
The vessel was to become part of the Navy in 2014, but difficult post-delivery problems have made the fate of this ambitious project unpleasant.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels, ordered by the Navy in 2007, will replace the aging Bremen-class frigates.
It is obvious that they will be equipped with powerful cannon, a number of anti-aircraft and anti-ship ballistic missiles and certain hidden technologies such as reduced radar and infrared and acoustic elements.
Other important features include long service life  it should be possible to deploy the latest frigates for up to two years outside the home port.
But the constant delays mean that the high-end naval ships  that were supposed to enable Germany to send forces overseas  will be obsolete by the time they are commissioned, notes the newspaper Die Zeit.
The infamous F125 made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to commission the vessel and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy had ever returned a ship to the manufacturer after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons for the return, but the German media cited a number of major software flaws and defects in metal components that would render the warship unusable in combat.
The software flaws were particularly significant as the Baden-Wuerttemberg class vessel will be operated by a crew of some 120 seamen  half the workforce needed on the Bremen class frigates.
It also turned out that the ship was significantly overweight, which reduced its performance and limited the Navy's ability to add future innovation.
The 7,000-tonne Rheinland-Pfal is believed to be twice as heavy as similar class ships used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to the defects in the metal components, the cost of the whole project  including the training of the crew is also a problem.
It is said that the price has risen from the original EUR 2.2 billion to a staggering EUR 3.1 billion.
The problems with the latest frigates have become particularly significant in light of recent warnings that German naval power is declining.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament's defence committee, confirmed that the navy was indeed "finding ships fit for duty".
The representative stated that the problems were continuously being addressed as the old vessels were being decommissioned but no replacements were provided.
He lamented that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates were capable of becoming part of the navy's equipment.
The National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
A new study is underway at a bat habitat in the Scottish Highlands to uncover how bats use the landscape to hunt for food.
It is hoped that the findings of the research will shed new light on the behaviour of unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities for this species.
The study, carried out by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, will follow whistling and small-bodied bats, as well as brown long- and water-bates, at the Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key areas of this bat habitat to monitor bat activities throughout the year.
NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
A sound analysis of all the recordings will determine the frequency of the bats' calls and what each species is doing.
A habitat map and a report will be produced, which will create a detailed landscape picture of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, conservation adviser for the NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to identify the benefits of habitat management work, such as grassland creation, and best practice in maintaining wooded areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across Britain have been declining dramatically over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and land development that affect colonies and the natural environment.
Wind turbines and lighting, as well as fly traps and chemical treatments of building materials, and attacks by cats, can also pose a risk.
Bats aren't actually blind.
But because they hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when they hunt.
They use sophisticated echo-location techniques to track insects and obstacles in flight.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens, and 76,000 acres of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has trained specialists who regularly conduct surveys, check colonies, and sometimes even rescue work.
The organisation has even set up the first and only dedicated bat sanctuary at Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Residence manager David Thompson says it's the ideal territory for them.
"Here in Threave we have a great bat area", he said.
We have old buildings, lots of ancient trees, and the best habitat.
But there's still so much we don't know about bats, so the work we're doing here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need to survive.
It highlights the importance of bat control before any maintenance work is undertaken on the property, as it is possible that the unintentional destruction of one breeding habitat can kill up to 400 females and young, potentially wiping out the entire local population.
Bats are protected, and it's illegal to kill them, harass them, disrupt or destroy their colonies.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish representative of the Bat Conservation Trust, encourages the public to join in and help.
She said, "There's a lot to learn about our bats and a lot of species that we don't know how their populations are doing".
