Brexit: Britain will forever regret the losses of car manufacturers
Britain will "ever regret" losing its status as the world's leading car maker after Brexit, said company secretary Greg Clark.
He added that it was "worrying" that Toyota UK had told the BBC that if Britain left the EU without a deal, it would temporarily halt production at its Burnaston plant near Derby.
"A deal is necessary", said Clark.
A Japanese carmaker said that the impact of delays at the borders if no Brexit deal is reached could cost jobs.
The Burnaston plant, where Toyota's Auris and Avensis cars are produced, produced almost 150 000 cars last year, 90% of which were exported to other European Union countries.
"My view is that if Britain suddenly left the EU at the end of March, we would see a production shutdown at our factory", said Marvin Cooke, chief executive of Toyota in Burnston.
Other carmakers, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover in the UK, are spreading fears of a no-deal exit from the EU as far as the functioning of cross-border trade is concerned.
BMW, for example, is saying it will close its Mini car plant in Oxford just a month after Brexit.
The main concerns relate to what manufacturers describe as risks to the supply chain in the event of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota's production line is running on a 'pretty on time' basis, with parts from suppliers in the UK and EU being delivered within 37 minutes for cars made to order.
If the UK leaves the EU on 29 March without a deal, there could be disruption at the border, which could lead to delays and shortages of spare parts, according to the industry.
It would be impossible for Toyota to have parts in stock for more than one day at the Derbyshire plant, the company said, and thus stop production.
Mr Clark said Theresa May's plans to revive future relations with the EU were 'precisely calibrated to avoid these border checks'.
"We need a deal. We want the best deal that will allow, as I say, not only the current success, but also the opportunity to seize this opportunity", he told BBC Radio 4's Today programme.
The proof, not only from Toyota, but also from other manufacturers, is that we absolutely have to be able to continue what is a highly successful set of supply chains.
Toyota was unable to say how long the production would be halted, but warned that in the long term the added costs would reduce the competitiveness of the plant and ultimately at the expense of jobs.
Peter Tsouvallaris, who has worked at the Burnaston plant for 24 years and is the chairman of the unions at the plant, said that the members of the trade union organisations are increasingly concerned: I have experience that once these jobs are gone, they will never come back.
A government spokesman said: 'We have put in place a precise and reliable roadmap for our future relations with the EU.'
Trump's meeting with Rosenstein may be delayed again, White House reports
Donald Trump's high-level meeting with acting attorney general Rod Rosenstein may be postponed for another week as the Supreme Court battle with Brett Kavanaugh continues, the White House said Sunday.
Rosenstein oversees the work of Robert Mueller's Special Counsel, which investigates Russian election interference, ties between Trump aides and Russia, and possible obstruction of justice by the president.
Whether Trump fires the acting attorney general and threatens Mueller's independence, Washington's gossip has been rife for months.
Earlier this month, the New York Times reported that Rosenstein discussed wearing a camera to record conversations with Trump and the possibility of impeaching the president through the 25th Amendment.
Rosenstein denied the report.
But last Monday, he arrived at the White House surrounded by reports that he was about to resign.
Instead, a meeting was announced for Thursday with Trump, who was at the United Nations headquarters in New York at the time.
Trump stated that he would rather not have Rosenstein dismissed, but then the meeting was delayed to avoid a Senate Judiciary Committee hearing where Kavanaugh's testimony was being presented by one of the women who accused him of sexual harassment, Dr. Christine Blasey Ford.
On Friday, Trump ordered the FBI to investigate the charges against Kavanaugh for a week, delaying the full Senate vote once again.
Trump's press secretary, Sarah Sanders, appeared on the Fox News Channel on Sunday.
When asked about the Rosenstein meeting, she said, "No date has been set yet, it could be this week, maybe it will be postponed another week in view of everything else going on at the Supreme Court".
But we'll see, and I'll always keep the media up to date.
Some reporters disagree with this claim: Sanders hasn't held a press conference with the White House since September 10.
Host Chris Wallace asked why.
Sanders said that too few press conferences were not due to "screen aversion" from television reporters, although she said, "I don't agree with the fact that she's going to speak".
She then suggested that the number of direct contacts between Trump and the press would increase.
"The president is holding more Q&A sessions than any president before him", she added, without citing evidence.
The conferences will continue, Sanders said, but if the press could ask the president of the United States directly, it would be better than interviewing me.
We're trying to do this, and you've seen that we've been doing this for the last few weeks, and there's going to be a press conference where you can talk to the president of the United States.
Trump regularly receives questions when he leaves the White House or attends open sessions or press conferences with visiting senior officials.
Independent press conferences are a rarity.
This week in New York, the president probably showed why with his relaxed and sometimes bizarre look in front of the assembled reporters.
