Foreign buyers will be charged higher property tax when buying property in the UK
Foreign buyers will be charged a higher property tax when they buy property in the UK, with the extra money going to help the homeless under Tory's new plans
This act will neutralize the success of Corbyn's move, which aims to attract young voters
The increase in the property tax will apply to non-taxable persons in the UK
It is expected to increase the national treasury by £ 120 million a year to help homeless people
Foreign buyers will pay higher property taxes when they buy property in the UK, with the extra money used to help the homeless, Theresa May announced today.
This act will be seen as an attempt to neutralize the success of Jeremy Corbyn's campaign to attract young voters with promises to provide more affordable housing and focus on high-income people.
The property tax increase will target individuals and businesses who do not pay UK taxes, with the extra money to bolster the government's efforts to combat sleepless nights.
The surcharge, which is in addition to the current obligation to pay property tax, including the higher levels introduced two years ago for second homes and purchase for rental purposes, can reach up to three per cent.
It is estimated that the state treasury will be increased by up to £120 million a year.
Estimates say that 13 percent of newly built properties in London are bought by non-UK residents, driving down prices and making it harder for first-time buyers to climb the home ladder.
Many wealthy areas of the country - especially in the capital - have become "ghost towns" precisely because of the high number of foreign buyers who spend most of their time outside the country.
The new policy came just weeks after Boris Johnson called for a reduction in property taxes to help more young people get their first home.
He accused the big construction companies of keeping property prices high by taking land but not using it, and urged Mrs May to withdraw quotas from affordable housing to fix Britain's "housing shortage".
Mr Corbyn has announced a number of exciting proposed housing reforms, including rental management and ending 'unusual' evictions.
He also wants to increase the authority of the committees to build new homes.
Mrs May said: "Last year I said I wanted to dedicate my efforts as Prime Minister to rebuilding the British dream so that every new generation has a better life.
And that means fixing our damaged real estate market.
Britain will always be open to people who want to live, work and make a life here.
But it cannot be right to make it easy for non-UK residents and foreign companies to buy homes as hard as hard-working UK residents.
For many people, the dream of a home is too distant and the shame of sleeping without a roof over one's head too real.
Jack Ross: "My highest ambition is to rule Scotland".
Sunderland boss Jack Ross says it's his "highest ambition" to become Scotland manager at some point.
The 42-year-old Scot is enjoying the challenge of rebuilding the North-East club, which currently sits in third place in the Premier League, just three points below the top.
He moved to the Stadium of Light this summer after leading St Mirren back to the Scottish Premiership last season.
I wanted to play for my country as a player.
I got a B grade and that was it, Ross told BBC Scotland's Sportsound.
But I grew up watching Scotland in the Hampden with my dad when I was a kid, and that's always something that draws me back.
But such an opportunity would only come if I was successful in running the club.
Ross' predecessors as manager of Sunderland were Dick Advocaat, David Moyes, Sam Allardyce, Martin O'Neill, Roy Keane, Gus Poyet and Paulo Di Canio. He was also the manager of the club from 2007 to 2011.
The former boss of Alloa Athletic says he felt no anxiety about following such established names at such a big club, having previously turned down forwards from Barnsley and Ipswich Town.
"Success for me at the time would have been measured by the question of whether I could get this club back into the Premier League.
"The structure and equipment of this club makes it a Premier League club", he said.
It's not an easy task to get him back, but I think I'd feel successful if I could just get the club back.
Ross has only had a three-year managerial career, having previously served as an assistant manager at Dumarton and spent 15 months as a Hearts coach.
He then helped Alloa recover from relegation to the third tier and transformed St Mirren from a starting relegation to championship winners the following season.
And Ross says he feels much better now than he has ever felt in his career with Clyde, Hartlepool, Falkirk, St Mirren and Hamilton Academical.
"They were probably real crossroads", he recalls, "when Alloa was taken".
I really believed that directing was the right thing for me, more than acting.
It sounds weird, because I was good, I made good money, and I enjoyed the heights.
But acting can be challenging.
There's a lot of stuff you have to go through every week.
I'm still going through them in terms of the stress and pressure of the job, but I just feel good about being in charge.
I've always wanted to be a manager, and now that I'm doing it, I feel like I'm in my own skin the most in my entire adult life.
