Peter Martin of the CGA consultancy, who produced the final reports, said: Stable sunshine and England's longer-than-expected World Cup appearance meant that July followed a similar pattern to the previous June, when pub attendance increased by 2.8 per cent, but restaurants were even more affected.
The decline in restaurant sales of 1.8% in June worsened in July.
Drinks and bars have fared the best, as have restaurants.
Restaurants, whose main revenue is from food, also suffered from the sun, though not as dramatically as restaurant operators.
Looks like people just wanted to get out for a drink.
Between controlled values and bars, beverage sales rose by 6.6 percent for the month, while food sales fell by three percent.
Paul Newman, of the leisure and hospitality analytics firm, said: "These results are a continuation of the trend that has been ongoing since the end of April.
Weather and the impact of major social or sporting events are the biggest factors when it comes to sales outside the domestic market.
It is no surprise that restaurant chains continue to struggle, although a 4.8 percent annual decline in sales will be particularly painful in light of ongoing cost pressures.
A long hot summer can't be a bad time for food-hungry business owners, and time will tell whether the milder temperatures we experienced in August will bring much-needed relief.
The overall growth in pubs and restaurants, including newly opened ones, was 2.7 per cent in July, reflecting a slowdown in brand presentation.
The Coffer Peach Tracker, the UK's pub, bar and restaurant industry sales monitor, collects and analyses performance data from 47 operating groups with combined turnover of over £9 billion, which is the industry standard for the sector.
