The tsunami also hit the western Donggala in 1996, claiming nine lives.
Indonesia is located on the seismic Pacific Ring of Fire and is regularly hit by earthquakes.
Here is a list of some of the largest earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: A major earthquake on the west coast of Aceh province in northern Sumatra, Indonesia, on December 26 caused a tsunami that affected 14 countries and killed 226,000 people along the Indian Ocean coast, more than half of them in Aceh province.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds of people died on the island of Nias, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8 magnitude earthquake struck the south of Indonesia's most populous island of Java, causing a tsunami that hit the southern coast and killed nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6 magnitude earthquake struck near Padang, the capital of West Sumatra.
More than 1,100 people lost their lives.
2010: A 7.5 magnitude earthquake struck one of the Mentawai Islands, near Sumatra, causing a 10-meter tsunami that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A minor earthquake hit the Pidie Jaya Regency in Aceh Province, causing destruction and panic as it reminded people of the devastating effects of the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
